Project Description

Demonstrate how to access Twitter data using rtweet package. Follow instructions for each section and include text annotation/ interpretation of results! What can be concluded based on the data investigation?

Retrieve most recent 3200 timelines of Trump and Biden

  • use: JoeBiden and realDonaldTrump
  • dont exclude anything
  • save to csv file, so you dont have to call the api subsequently, in case of long delays
  • read the csv file into a dataframe and use that df for subsequent analysis.
    • You will notice using the View (df) function that the the object structure of the original dataframe after the AP call is different from the one you read in. The original has embedded list objects, whereas the one read in is flattend. Also the date/time fields such as create_at is char rather than Twitters POSIX time format. Use lubridate datetime functions (eg: as_datetime) to convert. Show the column names
## tmls <- get_timelines(c("JoeBiden", "realDonaldTrump"), n = 3200)
## write_as_csv(tmls, "tweets.csv")
timelinesdf <- read_twitter_csv("tweets.csv")
# Convert the date field to a datetime
timelinesdf$created_at <- as_datetime(timelinesdf$created_at)

#Changed some fields to factors for easier manipulation later
timelinesdf$status_id <- as.factor(timelinesdf$status_id)
timelinesdf$screen_name <- as.factor(timelinesdf$screen_name)

# Fix up the reply count field.  It should be a int and NAs set to 0
timelinesdf$reply_count[is.na(timelinesdf$reply_count)] <- 0
timelinesdf$reply_count <- as.integer(timelinesdf$reply_count)

Retweets, Replies, and Original Tweets Aggregated over Months for Biden

df_biden_2 <- timelinesdf %>%
  mutate(mon = floor_date(created_at, 'month')) %>%
  mutate(original = is_retweet==FALSE & is_quote==FALSE & is.na(reply_to_status_id)) %>%
  filter(screen_name == 'JoeBiden' & created_at > '2020-02-01') %>%
  group_by(mon) %>%
  summarise(retweet_count = sum(retweet_count), 
            replies_count = sum(reply_count), 
            orig_count = sum(original))

  • mon: dates span from the month of feb through month of Oct.Note - the dates were only through the middle of October and not a complete month. This suggests that activity might increase dramatically for October
  • retweet_count: A max of 5.5million retweets. A staggering number of monthly retweet totals.
  • replies_count: this column was empty in the dataset. Investigating further, this attribute is only available with the premium API twitter access (see URL below).
  • orig_count: This represents the total number of original Tweets by Biden per month. Fairly consistent with a mean of 227.

https://stackoverflow.com/questions/47851662/reply-count-attribute-missing-from-tweet-object

df_biden_2 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = mon)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = retweet_count , color = "retweet"), linetype="dotdash") +
  geom_line(aes(y = replies_count , color = "replies"), linetype="dotdash") +
  geom_line(aes(y = orig_count , color = "original"), linetype="dotdash") +
  scale_color_manual(name = "Legend",
                       values = c("retweet" = "red", 
                                  "replies" = "blue", 
                                  "original" = "black")) +
  scale_y_continuous(trans='log10') +
  theme(
    legend.position = "right",
    plot.title = ggplot2::element_text(face = "bold")) +
  ggplot2::labs(
    x = NULL, y = "Tweets",
    title = "Biden Retweets, Original Tweets, and Replies Over Months",
    subtitle = "01 February 2020 to 09 2020"
  )
## Warning: Transformation introduced infinite values in continuous y-axis

Plotting the three different values on a log scale, you see exactly those observations. The number of total retweets is steadily increasing overtime and Bidens original tweet activity is reasonably consistent.

Plot the frequency of tweets for each user

by days

## plot the frequency of tweets for each user over time
timelinesdf %>%
  dplyr::group_by(screen_name) %>%
  ts_plot("days", trim = 0L) +
  ggplot2::geom_line() +
  ggplot2::theme_minimal() +
  ggplot2::theme(
    legend.title = ggplot2::element_blank(),
    legend.position = "right",
    plot.title = ggplot2::element_text(face = "bold")) +
  ggplot2::labs(
    x = NULL, y = NULL,
    title = "Frequency of Tweets by Candidate by Day",
    subtitle = "Last 3,200 Tweets per candidate retreived",
    caption = "\nSource: Data collected from Twitter's REST API via rtweet"
  )

This plot visualizes the point that was made above with the compressed window of time. Trumps tweet volume hit the 3,200 tweet limit in August, where as Biden overall has had much less activity and therefore we see a longer time line.

This visual also nicely shows the volume of activity per day of Biden vs.Trump. While it has increased for Biden during the period we have for Trump, we can see the overall per day tweets from Trump is about 5-8x that of Biden.

# Fix up the reply count field.  It should be a int and NAs set to 0

Plot hourly timeline of tweets

election_hastag %>%
  ts_plot("hours", trim = 0L) +
  ggplot2::geom_line() +
  ggplot2::theme(
    plot.title = ggplot2::element_text(face = "bold")) +
  ggplot2::labs(
    x = NULL, y = NULL,
    title = "Frequency of Tweets with #2020 Hashtag",
    subtitle = "Oct 16, 2020 to Oct 19, 2020",
    caption = "\nSource: Data collected from Twitter's REST API via rtweet"
  )

This time series is plotting 5,000 tweets on an hourly basis. The scale on the X-axis shows the daily spacing and the peaks and valleys of the data shows a frequency of activity ramping up around 8:00 am Eastern Time and then maintaining a push through 8:00 pm eastern.

This consistency probably suggests that most of these tweets are from the United States. If they were global, we wouldnt see the consistent up and down pattern we see here.

We can explore this next.

Note: Twitter returns time in UTC format. Therefore UTC 12:00 pm will be 8:00 am eastern time. https://developer.twitter.com/en/docs/twitter-ads-api/timezones

# Clean up some of the obvious data discrepancies.  This is an impossible task to fully clean up, but for the purpose of the "top 10" results we can make it more accurate.
election_hastag$location[election_hastag$location == "Washington, DC"] <- "Washington D.C."
election_hastag$location[election_hastag$location == "Washington, D.C."] <- "Washington D.C."
election_hastag$location[election_hastag$location == "United States of America"] <- "USA"
election_hastag$location[election_hastag$location == "California"] <- "California, USA"
election_hastag$location[election_hastag$location == "Texas"] <- "Texas, USA"
loc <- election_hastag %>%
  select(location) %>%
  group_by(location) %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  tally(sort = TRUE, name = "count") %>%
  head(n = 15L)
loc[1:10,] %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_col(aes(x = reorder(location, count), y = count)) + 
  coord_flip() +
  ggplot2::labs(
    x = "Count", 
    y = "Location",
    title = "Where Twitter users are from - Unique Locations",
    caption = "\nSource: Data collected from Twitter's REST API via rtweet"
  )

As suspected, The top 10 tweets show US based locations. Position 15 shows Melbourne as the location. Which could be either Australia or Florida, which has the same spelling as the Australian city. Of course, this is to be expected because its a US election, however, the US does effect the global economy so it tends to be watched by many people around the world.
